WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.200
- The following is a conversation
with Jensen Huang,

00:00:03.800 --> 00:00:07.700
CEO of NVIDIA, one of the most
important and influential

00:00:07.740 --> 00:00:10.240
companies in the history
of human civilization.

00:00:11.080 --> 00:00:15.000
NVIDIA is the engine powering
the AI revolution, and a lot

00:00:15.040 --> 00:00:18.980
of its success can be directly
attributed to Jensen's sheer force of

00:00:19.080 --> 00:00:25.200
will and his many brilliant bets and decisions
as a leader, engineer, and innovator.

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:32.100
This is Lex Fridman Podcast. And now
dear friends, here's Jensen Huang.

00:00:33.400 --> 00:00:37.360
You've propelled NVIDIA into a new era in

00:00:37.420 --> 00:00:41.380
AI, moving beyond its focus on chip
scale design to now rack scale

00:00:41.420 --> 00:00:45.360
design. And I think it's fair to
say that winning for NVIDIA for a

00:00:45.420 --> 00:00:49.320
long time used to be about building
the best GPU possible, and you still

00:00:49.420 --> 00:00:53.080
do, but now you've expanded
that to extreme co-design of

00:00:53.140 --> 00:00:56.700
GPU, CPU memory, networking,
storage, power cooling,

00:00:57.280 --> 00:01:01.160
software, the rack itself, the pod
that you've announced, and even the

00:01:01.220 --> 00:01:04.980
data center. So let's talk about
extreme co-design. What is the

00:01:05.019 --> 00:01:08.600
hardest part of co-designing
system with that many complex

00:01:08.640 --> 00:01:10.470
components and design variables?

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:11.930
- Yeah, thanks for that question.

00:01:12.820 --> 00:01:16.460
So first of all, the reason why extreme
co-design is necessary is because the

00:01:16.520 --> 00:01:22.780
problem no longer fits inside one
computer to be accelerated by one GPU.

00:01:24.620 --> 00:01:28.420
The problem that you're trying to
solve is you would like to go faster

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:32.840
than the number of computers
that you add. So you added

00:01:32.880 --> 00:01:36.580
you know, 10,000 computers, but you
would like it to go a million times

00:01:36.620 --> 00:01:42.000
faster. Then all of a sudden
you have to take the algorithm,

00:01:43.360 --> 00:01:45.820
you have to break up the algorithm,
you have to refactor it,

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:50.400
you have to shard the pipeline, you have
to shard the data, you have to shard the

00:01:50.460 --> 00:01:55.790
model. Now all of a sudden when you
distribute the problem this way,

00:01:56.610 --> 00:01:59.200
not just scaling up the problem, but
you're distributing the problem,

00:02:00.340 --> 00:02:04.280
then everything gets in the
way. This is the Amdahl's Law

00:02:04.360 --> 00:02:08.240
problem where the amount of
speed up you have for something

00:02:09.300 --> 00:02:13.040
depends on how much of the
total workload it is. And so

00:02:13.080 --> 00:02:20.670
if computation represents 50% of the problem,
and I sped up computation infinitely

00:02:21.120 --> 00:02:22.109
like a million times,

00:02:23.120 --> 00:02:25.820
you know, I only sped up the total
workload by a factor of two.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.790
Now all of a sudden, not only
do you have to distribute a

00:02:30.790 --> 00:02:33.800
computation, you have to, you
know, shard the pipeline somehow.

00:02:34.620 --> 00:02:37.100
You also have to solve
the networking problem

00:02:38.300 --> 00:02:42.160
because you've got all of these
computers are all connected together.

00:02:42.220 --> 00:02:45.060
And so distributed computing
at the scale that we do,

00:02:47.240 --> 00:02:51.100
the CPU is a problem, the GPU is a
problem, the networking is a problem, the

00:02:51.180 --> 00:02:55.020
switching is a problem. And
distributing the workload across all

00:02:55.060 --> 00:02:56.200
these computers is a problem.

00:02:57.100 --> 00:03:00.940
It's just a massively complex computer
science problem. And so we just

00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:08.700
gotta bring every technology to bear.
Otherwise, we scale up linearly or we

00:03:09.720 --> 00:03:13.600
scale up based on the capabilities
of Moore's Law, which has

00:03:13.720 --> 00:03:16.200
largely slowed because
Dennard scaling has slowed.

00:03:16.720 --> 00:03:19.880
- I'm sure there's trade-offs there.
Plus you have a complete disparate

00:03:20.240 --> 00:03:24.020
disciplines here. I'm sure you have specialists
in each one of these high bandwidth

00:03:24.100 --> 00:03:28.049
memory, the network and the NVLink,
the NICs, the optics and the

00:03:28.160 --> 00:03:31.760
copper that you're doing, the power delivery, the
cooling, all of that. I mean, there's like world

00:03:31.840 --> 00:03:34.950
experts in each of those. How do you get
'em in a room together to figure out-

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:37.730
- That's why my staff is so large.

00:03:37.760 --> 00:03:41.230
- What's the process—can you take me through
the process of the specialists and the

00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:45.180
generalists? Like how do you put
together the rack when you know the

00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:48.440
s- the set of things you have
to shove into a rack together?

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:51.200
Like what does that process look
like of designing it all together?

00:03:51.290 --> 00:03:54.920
- Yeah. There's the first question,
which is: what is extreme co-design?

00:03:55.280 --> 00:03:58.930
You're, you, we're optimizing
across the entire stack of software

00:03:59.440 --> 00:04:02.840
from architectures to chips, to
systems, to system software, to the

00:04:02.980 --> 00:04:06.890
algorithms, to the applications. That's
one layer. The second thing that you and

00:04:06.940 --> 00:04:10.760
I just talked about is goes
beyond CPUs and GPUs and

00:04:10.780 --> 00:04:14.480
networking chips and scale up
switches and scale out switches.

00:04:15.400 --> 00:04:19.380
And then of course, you gotta
include power and cooling and all

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:23.290
of that because, you know, all
these computers are extremely,

00:04:23.380 --> 00:04:27.260
extremely power hungry. They do
a lot of work and they're very

00:04:27.340 --> 00:04:31.070
energy efficient, but they in
aggregate still consume a lot of

00:04:31.100 --> 00:04:33.820
power. And so that's one. The
first question is, what is it?

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:38.300
The second question is, why is it, and
we just spoke about the reason, you

00:04:38.340 --> 00:04:42.260
know you want to distribute the
workload so that you can exceed

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:46.580
the benefit of just increasing
the number of computers.

00:04:47.400 --> 00:04:51.070
And then the third question is,
how is it, how do you do it?

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:55.250
And that's the, that's kind
of the miracle of this

00:04:55.280 --> 00:04:59.030
company. You know, when you're designing a
computer, you have to have operating system of

00:04:59.060 --> 00:05:01.880
computers. When you're
designing a company,

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:06.700
you should first think about what is it that you
want the company to produce. You know, I see

00:05:06.760 --> 00:05:09.110
a lot of companies organization
charts, and they all look the same.

00:05:09.910 --> 00:05:13.660
Hamburger organization charts,
soft organization charts, and car

00:05:13.680 --> 00:05:15.550
company organization charts.
They all look the same.

00:05:16.360 --> 00:05:19.960
And it doesn't make any sense to me. You
know, the goal of a company is to be the

00:05:20.080 --> 00:05:24.760
company is to be the machinery, the
mechanism, the system that produces

00:05:25.840 --> 00:05:28.920
the output. And that output is the
product that we like to create.

00:05:29.820 --> 00:05:33.340
It is also designed, the architecture
of the company should reflect

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:37.540
the environment by which it
exists. It almost indirectly

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:42.570
says what you should do with the
organization. My direct staff is 60 people.

00:05:43.740 --> 00:05:47.660
You know, I don't have one-on-ones with 'em because it's
impossible. You can't have, you can't have 60 people

00:05:47.700 --> 00:05:51.030
on your staff if you're, you
know, gonna get work done and-

00:05:51.260 --> 00:05:53.610
- So you still have 60 reports.
You still have across-

00:05:53.610 --> 00:05:53.920
- More, yeah.

00:05:54.160 --> 00:05:58.860
- More. And most stars at least
have a foot in engineering.

00:05:59.720 --> 00:06:00.460
- Almost all of them.

00:06:01.380 --> 00:06:05.300
There's experts in memory, there's
experts in CPUs, there's experts in

00:06:05.700 --> 00:06:06.390
optical. All, all—

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:06.860
- That's incredible.

00:06:06.880 --> 00:06:11.906
- Yeah, GPUs and— Architecture,
algorithms, design, um—

00:06:11.916 --> 00:06:15.456
- So, you constantly have an eye on the
entire stack, and you're having to, like,

00:06:15.516 --> 00:06:18.466
intense discussions about the
designer of the entire stack?

00:06:18.486 --> 00:06:21.936
- And no conversation is ever one
person. That's why I don't do

00:06:22.076 --> 00:06:24.026
one-on-ones. We present a problem

00:06:24.856 --> 00:06:29.216
and all of us attack it. You know,
because we're doing extreme co-design.

00:06:30.016 --> 00:06:32.956
And literally, the company is doing
extreme co-design all the time.

00:06:33.536 --> 00:06:37.556
- So, even if you're talking about a
particular component, like cooling,

00:06:38.656 --> 00:06:40.876
networking, everybody's listening in?

00:06:40.936 --> 00:06:41.366
- Yeah, exactly.

00:06:41.366 --> 00:06:44.816
- And they can contribute, "Well, this
doesn't work for the power distribution.

00:06:44.876 --> 00:06:45.266
This doesn't-"

00:06:45.616 --> 00:06:45.816
- Exactly.

00:06:45.826 --> 00:06:49.096
- "... This doesn't work for the
memory. This doesn't work for this."

00:06:49.556 --> 00:06:54.096
- Exactly. And whoever wants to tune out,
tune out. You know what I'm saying?

00:06:54.136 --> 00:06:57.726
And the reason for that is because the
people who are on the staff, they know

00:06:58.096 --> 00:07:01.676
when to pay attention. There's supposed...
You know, it's something they could have

00:07:01.696 --> 00:07:04.616
contributed to, they didn't contribute to,
"I'm going to call them out." You know?

00:07:04.656 --> 00:07:06.036
And so, "Hey, come on, let's get in here."

00:07:07.236 --> 00:07:11.306
- So, as you mentioned, NVIDIA is this
company that's adapting to the environment.

00:07:11.496 --> 00:07:15.306
So, at which point can you say,
did the environment change and

00:07:15.336 --> 00:07:19.056
began adapting sort of secretly-

00:07:19.276 --> 00:07:23.216
... in the early days from
GPU for gaming, maybe the

00:07:23.276 --> 00:07:26.976
early deep learning revolution to we're
now going to start thinking of it as an AI

00:07:27.016 --> 00:07:31.336
factory? What does NVIDIA do? It produces
AI, let's build a factory that makes AI.

00:07:32.176 --> 00:07:34.456
- Uh, I could, I c- you, you could- I could
reason through what just systematically.

00:07:35.256 --> 00:07:38.216
We started out as a, as
an accelerator company.

00:07:39.096 --> 00:07:42.616
But the problem with accelerators is that
the application domain's too narrow.

00:07:43.136 --> 00:07:46.936
It has the benefit of being
incredibly optimized for the

00:07:47.016 --> 00:07:50.576
job. You know, any specialist has
that benefit. The problem with

00:07:51.236 --> 00:07:55.876
intense specialization is that, of
course, your market reach is narrower,

00:07:57.036 --> 00:08:02.326
but that's, that's even fine. The
problem is, the market size also

00:08:03.316 --> 00:08:10.576
dictates your R&amp;D capacity. And your
R&amp;D capacity ultimately dictates

00:08:10.696 --> 00:08:14.556
the influence and impact that you can
possibly have in computing. And so,

00:08:14.616 --> 00:08:18.896
when we first started out as an
accelerator, very specific accelerator,

00:08:19.716 --> 00:08:23.686
we always knew that had- that was going
to be our first step. We had to find a

00:08:23.696 --> 00:08:27.516
way to become accelerated computing.
But the problem is, when you become a

00:08:27.556 --> 00:08:28.336
computing company,

00:08:29.576 --> 00:08:33.396
it's too general purpose and it takes
away from your specialization. The

00:08:33.496 --> 00:08:37.136
tur- I connected two
words that are actually

00:08:37.936 --> 00:08:41.856
have fundamental tension. The better
computing company we become, the

00:08:41.916 --> 00:08:45.836
worse we became as a specialist.
The more of a specialist, the less

00:08:45.876 --> 00:08:49.556
capacity we have to do
overall computing. And so,

00:08:49.916 --> 00:08:53.826
that... And I connected those two words
together on purpose, that the company

00:08:53.876 --> 00:09:01.476
has to find that really narrow path,
step by step by step, to expand our

00:09:01.576 --> 00:09:05.216
aperture of computing, but not
give up on the most important

00:09:05.316 --> 00:09:09.156
specialization that we had. Okay, so
the first step that we took beyond

00:09:09.236 --> 00:09:12.776
acceleration was, we invented
a programmable pixel shader.

00:09:13.476 --> 00:09:17.456
So, that was the first step towards
programmability. You know, it was our

00:09:17.536 --> 00:09:21.396
first journey towards moving into the world
of computing. The second thing that we

00:09:21.436 --> 00:09:25.596
did was we created we put

00:09:25.676 --> 00:09:33.636
FP32 into our shaders. That FP32 step,
IEEE-compatible FP32, was a huge step

00:09:33.756 --> 00:09:39.396
in the direction of computing. It was the
reason why all of the people who were

00:09:39.436 --> 00:09:43.216
working on, on stream
processors and, you know,

00:09:43.356 --> 00:09:47.306
other types of data flow processors
discovered us. And they said, "Hey, all of

00:09:47.336 --> 00:09:51.136
a sudden, you know, we might be able to use
this GPU that's incredibly computationally

00:09:51.156 --> 00:09:55.086
intensive, and it's now, you
know, compliant with IEEE."

00:09:55.276 --> 00:09:58.836
I can take my software that I was
writing, you know, previously on

00:09:58.876 --> 00:10:03.295
CPUs, and I can, you know, see about,
you know, using the GPU for that.

00:10:04.676 --> 00:10:08.336
And which led us to
create, put C on top of

00:10:08.396 --> 00:10:12.316
FP32, what's called, we
call Cg. The Cg path

00:10:12.396 --> 00:10:17.176
took us to eventually CUDA.
CUDA, step by step by step

00:10:17.996 --> 00:10:21.956
We... Well, putting CUDA
on GeForce, that was

00:10:22.016 --> 00:10:25.896
a strategic decision that was very,
very hard to do, because it cost the

00:10:25.936 --> 00:10:29.816
company enormous amounts of our
profits, and we couldn't afford it

00:10:29.855 --> 00:10:33.766
at the time. But we did it anyways
because we wanted to be a computing

00:10:33.816 --> 00:10:37.156
company. A computing
company has a computing

00:10:37.236 --> 00:10:41.166
architecture. A computing architecture
has to be compatible across all of

00:10:41.196 --> 00:10:42.276
the chips that we build.

00:10:42.456 --> 00:10:46.176
- Can you take me through that decision? So,
putting CUDA on GeForce, could not afford to

00:10:46.216 --> 00:10:52.276
do? Can you explain that decision? Why,
why boldly choose to do that anyway?

00:10:52.296 --> 00:10:53.456
Can you explain that decision?

00:10:53.496 --> 00:10:57.416
- Yeah, excellent. That was, that was
the first... I would say that that was

00:10:57.996 --> 00:11:06.576
the first strategic decision that is
as close to an existential threat.

00:11:06.976 --> 00:11:10.336
- For people who don't know, it
turned out to be, spoiler alert,

00:11:10.856 --> 00:11:14.756
one of the most incredibly
brilliant decisions ever made

00:11:14.816 --> 00:11:16.816
by a company. So, CUDA turned out to be

00:11:18.276 --> 00:11:23.536
an incredible foundation for computation
in this AI infrastructure world. So-

00:11:23.976 --> 00:11:24.086
- Thank you

00:11:24.086 --> 00:11:27.156
- ... just setting the context. It
turned out to be a good decision.

00:11:27.296 --> 00:11:31.176
- Yeah, it turned out to have been a good
decision. I think the... So, here's the way it

00:11:31.236 --> 00:11:34.996
went. So, we invented this
thing called CUDA, and

00:11:35.136 --> 00:11:38.716
It expanded the aperture of applications

00:11:38.796 --> 00:11:43.806
that, that we can accelerate with our
accelerator. The question is, how do we,

00:11:44.796 --> 00:11:47.276
how do we attract developers to CUDA?

00:11:48.476 --> 00:11:52.876
Because a computing platform is all
about developers. And developers

00:11:54.536 --> 00:11:58.336
don't come to a computing platform
just because, you know, it

00:11:58.376 --> 00:12:02.256
could perform something interesting. They
come to a computing platform because the

00:12:02.276 --> 00:12:03.236
install base is large.

00:12:04.076 --> 00:12:07.756
Because a developer, like anybody
else, wants to develop software that

00:12:07.856 --> 00:12:11.436
reaches a lot of people. So,
the install base is, in fact,

00:12:11.736 --> 00:12:14.516
the single most important
part of an architecture. The

00:12:14.526 --> 00:12:19.336
architecture could attract enormous
amounts of criticism. For example,

00:12:20.456 --> 00:12:23.536
no architecture has ever
attracted more criticism than the

00:12:23.716 --> 00:12:31.564
x86.... you know, as a less than, less than
elegant architecture, but yet it is the

00:12:31.584 --> 00:12:35.524
defining architecture of today. It
gives you an example that in fact

00:12:35.564 --> 00:12:40.684
so many RISC architectures which
were beautifully architected,

00:12:42.284 --> 00:12:46.184
incredibly well-designed by some of the
brightest computer scientists in the

00:12:46.204 --> 00:12:49.774
world, largely failed.
And so I've given you two

00:12:49.864 --> 00:12:53.714
examples where one is, you know,
one is elegant, the other one's

00:12:53.724 --> 00:12:58.534
barely aesthetic, and so yet x86
survived and the reason for-

00:12:58.534 --> 00:12:59.204
- Install base is everything.

00:12:59.304 --> 00:13:03.264
- Install base defines an
architecture. Not... Everything else

00:13:03.304 --> 00:13:07.104
is secondary, okay? And so there were
other architectures at the time.

00:13:07.424 --> 00:13:11.294
CUDA came out, OpenCL was here. There were...
You know, there's several other competing

00:13:11.364 --> 00:13:15.324
architectures. But the thing that...
The decision that we made that was good

00:13:15.384 --> 00:13:18.424
was we said, "Hey, look,
ultimately it's about,

00:13:19.344 --> 00:13:23.304
Install base and what is the
best way we could get a new

00:13:23.344 --> 00:13:24.924
computing architecture into the world?"

00:13:26.464 --> 00:13:30.434
By that timeframe, GeForce had
become successful. We were already

00:13:30.443 --> 00:13:33.924
selling millions and millions
of GeForce GPUs a year, and we

00:13:33.944 --> 00:13:37.044
said, "You know, we ought
to put CUDA on GeForce

00:13:38.284 --> 00:13:42.344
and put it into every single PC
whether customers use it or not,

00:13:43.784 --> 00:13:47.504
and use it as a starting point of
cultivating our install base."

00:13:48.024 --> 00:13:52.024
Meanwhile, we'll go and
attract developers, and

00:13:52.864 --> 00:13:56.224
we went to universities
and wrote books and taught

00:13:56.324 --> 00:14:00.244
classes and put CUDA everywhere.
And eventually people discover...

00:14:00.284 --> 00:14:04.004
And at the time, the PC was the primary
computing vehicle. There was no

00:14:04.124 --> 00:14:07.734
cloud, and we could put a
supercomputer in the hands of every

00:14:07.824 --> 00:14:11.284
researcher in school, every scientist, you
know, every engineering school, every...

00:14:11.364 --> 00:14:15.224
or every student in school, and
eventually something amazing will happen.

00:14:15.644 --> 00:14:19.064
Well, the problem was
CUDA increased our cost

00:14:19.944 --> 00:14:23.424
of that GPU, which is a consumer
product, so tremendously,

00:14:23.464 --> 00:14:28.664
it completely consumed all of the
company's gross profit dollars.

00:14:29.564 --> 00:14:33.484
And so at the time, the company was probably,
you know, worth, I don't know, at the time,

00:14:33.864 --> 00:14:34.043
eight...

00:14:36.024 --> 00:14:39.694
Was it like $8 billion or something? Like
six, $7 billion or something like that.

00:14:40.504 --> 00:14:46.944
After we launched CUDA, I recognized
that it was going to add so much cost,

00:14:47.044 --> 00:14:49.244
but it was something we believed in.

00:14:50.104 --> 00:14:53.684
You know, our market cap went down to like
one and a half billion dollars. And so

00:14:54.224 --> 00:14:58.024
we were down, we were down
there for a while and we

00:14:58.084 --> 00:15:01.844
clawed our way way back
slowly, but we carried

00:15:01.904 --> 00:15:05.574
CUDA on GeForce. I always say
that NVIDIA is the house that

00:15:05.604 --> 00:15:09.564
GeForce built, because it was
GeForce that took CUDA out to

00:15:09.644 --> 00:15:17.444
everybody. Researchers, scientists, they
discovered CUDA on GeForce because they were

00:15:17.464 --> 00:15:21.364
all, you know... Many of 'em were
gamers. Many of them built their own

00:15:21.424 --> 00:15:25.344
PCs anyways. In a university
lab, many of them built

00:15:25.404 --> 00:15:28.764
clusters themselves, you know,
using PC components. And,

00:15:29.364 --> 00:15:31.284
and so that, you know, that's
kind of how we got going.

00:15:31.504 --> 00:15:35.024
- And then that became the platform and the
foundation for the deep learning revolution.

00:15:35.324 --> 00:15:37.744
- That was also another great,
great observation. Yeah.

00:15:38.264 --> 00:15:41.924
- That existential moment, do you
remember... Like, what were those meetings

00:15:42.004 --> 00:15:47.044
