00:17:34.464 --> 00:17:38.274
And so I believe it in my mind,
and when I believe it in my mind,

00:17:38.724 --> 00:17:42.444
you know, you know how it is.
You manifest a future and that

00:17:42.484 --> 00:17:47.304
future is so convincing,
there's no way it won't happen.

00:17:48.184 --> 00:17:52.784
There's a lot of suffering in between, but
you've gotta believe what you believe.

00:17:52.964 --> 00:17:55.784
- So you envision the future-

00:17:55.794 --> 00:17:59.484
... and you essentially, from a sort of
engineering perspective, manifest it?

00:17:59.804 --> 00:18:03.704
- Yeah. And you, you reason about how
to get there. You reason about why

00:18:03.784 --> 00:18:09.944
it, it must exist. And, you
know, I reason... We all

00:18:09.984 --> 00:18:12.804
reason it here. The management team would
reason about it. All the people that I...

00:18:13.524 --> 00:18:17.504
We spend a lot of time reasoning about
it. The thing, the thing that... The next

00:18:17.544 --> 00:18:19.574
part of it is probably a
skill thing, which is,

00:18:20.464 --> 00:18:23.874
you know, oftentimes in
leadership the leadership

00:18:24.204 --> 00:18:27.904
stays quiet or they learn about something,
and then they do some manifesto,

00:18:28.524 --> 00:18:32.424
and it's a brand-new year, and somehow
at the end of the year, next year,

00:18:32.484 --> 00:18:36.324
we're gonna have a brand-new plan.
Big huge layoff this way, big huge

00:18:36.424 --> 00:18:39.004
organization change this way, new mission

00:18:39.124 --> 00:18:43.520
statement... brand new logos
you know, that kind of stuff.

00:18:43.920 --> 00:18:48.230
Um, we've just never, I never do things
that way. When I learn about something

00:18:48.880 --> 00:18:52.560
and it's starting to influence how
I think, I'll make it very clear to

00:18:52.620 --> 00:18:56.160
everybody near me that, you
know, this, this is interesting.

00:18:57.160 --> 00:19:01.080
This is going to make a difference.
This is going to impact that.

00:19:01.700 --> 00:19:05.640
And I reason about things step by step by
step. Oftentimes, I've already made up

00:19:05.660 --> 00:19:09.330
my mind, but I'll take
every possible opportunity,

00:19:09.400 --> 00:19:12.940
external information, new
insights, new discoveries,

00:19:13.380 --> 00:19:16.800
New engineering, you
know, revelations, new

00:19:16.920 --> 00:19:20.860
milestones developed, I'll take
those opportunities and I'll use

00:19:20.920 --> 00:19:24.020
it to shape everybody else's

00:19:24.700 --> 00:19:28.320
belief system. And I'm doing
that literally every single day.

00:19:28.880 --> 00:19:32.800
I'm doing that with my board, I'm doing that
with my management team, I'm doing that with

00:19:32.840 --> 00:19:34.720
my employees. I'm trying to shape

00:19:35.840 --> 00:19:41.980
their belief systems such that when I come
the day I say, "Hey, let's buy Mellanox,"

00:19:43.840 --> 00:19:47.460
it's completely obvious to everybody
that we absolutely should.

00:19:48.120 --> 00:19:52.100
On the day that I said, "Hey guys, let's

00:19:52.140 --> 00:19:56.050
go all in on deep learning,"
and let me tell you why. I've

00:19:56.100 --> 00:20:00.010
already been laying down the
bricks to different organizations

00:20:00.040 --> 00:20:04.300
inside the company. Every
organization and everybody,

00:20:05.400 --> 00:20:07.000
many of the people might
have heard everything.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:10.500
Most of the company hears,
of course, pieces of it.

00:20:11.460 --> 00:20:13.260
And on the day that I announce it,

00:20:14.320 --> 00:20:18.240
everybody's kind of bought
in to many pieces of it.

00:20:19.360 --> 00:20:24.250
And in a lot of ways, I like to
announce these things, and I imagine,

00:20:25.260 --> 00:20:29.710
that the employees are kind of saying,
"You know, Jensen, what took you so long?"

00:20:30.820 --> 00:20:34.760
And in fact, I've been shaping their
belief system for some time, and therefore

00:20:34.800 --> 00:20:38.630
leadership. Sometimes it looks
like you're leading from behind,

00:20:39.580 --> 00:20:43.320
but you've been shaping their, you know, to
the point where on the day that I declared it,

00:20:43.720 --> 00:20:47.310
100% buy-in. But that's what you
want. You want to bring everybody

00:20:47.360 --> 00:20:51.309
along. You know, otherwise, we announce something
about deep learning and everybody goes, "What

00:20:51.320 --> 00:20:55.220
are you talking about?" You know, you
announce something about let's go all in

00:20:55.280 --> 00:20:59.029
on this thing, and your
management team, your

00:20:59.060 --> 00:21:02.590
board, your employees, your customers, they're
kind of like, "Where's this coming from?

00:21:02.880 --> 00:21:06.620
You know, this is insane." And so, so GTC

00:21:06.720 --> 00:21:10.060
effect, if you go back in time,
you look at the keynotes,

00:21:11.760 --> 00:21:15.350
I'm also shaping the belief
system of my partners in the

00:21:15.420 --> 00:21:19.180
industry and I'm using that to
shape, you know, the belief

00:21:19.200 --> 00:21:23.420
system of my own employees. And so by
the time that I announce something,

00:21:24.360 --> 00:21:26.680
like for example, we just announced Grok.

00:21:27.960 --> 00:21:31.920
We've been late... I've been talking about
the stepping stones for two and a half

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:32.240
years.

00:21:33.500 --> 00:21:37.280
You just go back and go, "Oh my gosh,
they've been talking about it for two and a

00:21:37.320 --> 00:21:41.100
half years." And so I've been laying
the foundation step by step by step,

00:21:41.260 --> 00:21:44.230
so when the time comes you announce it, everybody's
saying, "You know, what took you so long?"

00:21:44.400 --> 00:21:48.340
- But it's not just inside the company. You're
shaping the landscape, the broader global landscape

00:21:48.380 --> 00:21:52.150
of innovation. Like, putting those ideas
out there, you really are manifesting

00:21:52.240 --> 00:21:52.720
reality.

00:21:53.180 --> 00:21:57.080
- We don't build computers. We actually
don't build clouds. We don't... As

00:21:57.120 --> 00:22:00.940
it turns out, we're a computing
platform company. And so nobody can

00:22:00.960 --> 00:22:05.420
buy anything from us. That's the
weird thing. You know, we vertically

00:22:06.900 --> 00:22:10.660
design, vertically integrate to
design and optimize, but then

00:22:10.680 --> 00:22:14.220
we open up the entire platform
at every single layer

00:22:14.840 --> 00:22:18.340
to be integrated into other
companies' products and services and

00:22:18.420 --> 00:22:21.650
clouds and supercomputers
and OEM computers

00:22:21.660 --> 00:22:25.600
and so the amazing thing
is, I can't do what I

00:22:25.640 --> 00:22:29.510
do without having convinced
them first. And so most of

00:22:29.520 --> 00:22:33.280
GTC is about manifesting
a future that by the

00:22:33.360 --> 00:22:38.560
time that we... My product is ready,
they're going, "What took you so long?"

00:22:39.460 --> 00:22:43.120
- Yeah. So one of the things you've
been a believer for a long

00:22:43.220 --> 00:22:47.140
time is scaling laws,
broadly defined. So are

00:22:47.180 --> 00:22:49.500
you still a believer in the scaling laws?

00:22:49.700 --> 00:22:51.080
- Yeah, yeah. Yeah, we have
more scaling laws now.

00:22:51.540 --> 00:22:55.140
- So I think you've outlined four of them
with pre-training, post-training, test

00:22:55.200 --> 00:23:01.150
time, and agentic scaling. What do you
think, when you think about the future,

00:23:01.920 --> 00:23:05.320
deep future and the near-term
future, what are the blockers

00:23:06.320 --> 00:23:10.240
that you're most concerned about that keep
you up at night that you have to overcome

00:23:10.940 --> 00:23:12.030
in order to keep scaling?

00:23:12.840 --> 00:23:16.580
- Well, we can go back and reflect on
what people thought were blockers.

00:23:16.620 --> 00:23:20.310
So in the beginning, we were the
first... The pre-training scaling

00:23:20.380 --> 00:23:24.130
law. You know, people
thought well rightfully

00:23:24.240 --> 00:23:28.140
so, that the amount of data that
we have, high-quality data that we

00:23:28.180 --> 00:23:32.020
have will limit the intelligence that
we achieve. And that scaling law

00:23:32.100 --> 00:23:35.720
was an important, very important
scaling law. The larger the model, the

00:23:35.800 --> 00:23:39.620
correspondingly more data
results in a better... With a

00:23:39.820 --> 00:23:43.720
results in a smarter AI. And
so that was pre-training. And

00:23:43.800 --> 00:23:47.750
Ilya Sutskever, Ilya said, "We're out of data,"
or something like that. "Pre-training is

00:23:47.800 --> 00:23:50.740
over," or something like
that. The industry panicked,

00:23:51.980 --> 00:23:55.880
you know, that this is the end of AI.
And of course, of course that, that's

00:23:56.040 --> 00:24:00.020
obviously not true. We're gonna keep
on scaling the amount of data that we

00:24:00.360 --> 00:24:03.670
have to, to train with. A lot of that
data is probably gonna be synthetic,

00:24:04.680 --> 00:24:08.200
and that also confused people,
you know? And what people don't

00:24:08.220 --> 00:24:11.980
realize is they've kind of
forgotten that most of the data

00:24:12.040 --> 00:24:15.960
that, that we are training that
we teach each other with, inform

00:24:15.980 --> 00:24:18.400
each other with, is
synthetic. You know, I...

00:24:19.450 --> 00:24:22.500
It's synthetic because it
didn't come out of nature.

00:24:23.620 --> 00:24:29.150
You created it. I'm consuming
it. I modify it, augment it,

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:33.920
I regenerate it, somebody
else consumes it. And so, so

00:24:33.980 --> 00:24:43.360
we've now reached a level where AI is able
to take ground truth, augment it......

00:24:43.500 --> 00:24:46.680
Enhance it, synthetically
generate an enormous amount of

00:24:46.720 --> 00:24:50.190
data. And that part of post-training

00:24:50.400 --> 00:24:52.840
continues to scale, and so the
amount of data that we could use

00:24:53.640 --> 00:24:57.380
that is human generated will be
smaller, and smaller, and smaller.

00:24:57.760 --> 00:25:01.870
The amount of data that
we use to train model,

00:25:02.720 --> 00:25:06.590
is going to continue to scale to the
point where we're no longer limited...

00:25:07.080 --> 00:25:11.040
Training is no longer limited by...
Data is now limited by compute. And the

00:25:11.060 --> 00:25:14.440
reason for that is most of the data
is synthetic. Then the next phase

00:25:15.660 --> 00:25:17.960
is test time, and

00:25:19.020 --> 00:25:22.950
I still remember people telling me
that, "Inference? Oh, yeah, that's

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:26.860
easy. Pre-training, that's hard." These
are giant systems that people are talking

00:25:26.920 --> 00:25:30.860
about. Inference must be easy. And so
inference chips are gonna be little tiny

00:25:30.980 --> 00:25:31.590
chips, and

00:25:32.020 --> 00:25:35.360
... you know, they're not, they're not like
NVIDIA's chips. Oh, those are gonna be

00:25:35.420 --> 00:25:39.470
complicated and expensive, and, you
know, we could make... And this is-

00:25:39.520 --> 00:25:43.200
in the future, inference is gonna be the
biggest market, and it's gonna be easy, and

00:25:43.540 --> 00:25:46.860
we're gonna commoditize it. You know,
everybody can build their own chips. And,

00:25:47.720 --> 00:25:52.770
and that was always illogical to
me because inference is thinking,

00:25:53.800 --> 00:25:59.460
and I think thinking is hard.
Thinking is way harder than reading.

00:25:59.540 --> 00:26:00.380
You know, pre-training is just

00:26:01.780 --> 00:26:05.620
memorization and generalization, you know,
and looking for patterns in relationships.

00:26:05.680 --> 00:26:13.100
You're reading and reading, versus thinking,
reasoning, solving problems, taking

00:26:14.840 --> 00:26:18.740
unexplored experiences,
new experiences, and

00:26:18.860 --> 00:26:22.820
breaking it down into...
Decomposing it into, you

00:26:22.860 --> 00:26:26.500
know, solvable pieces that we
then go off, either through first

00:26:26.580 --> 00:26:30.490
principle reasoning, or, you
know, through previous examples,

00:26:30.620 --> 00:26:34.610
prior experiences. You know, or just uh,

00:26:34.660 --> 00:26:38.410
exploration and search and,
you know, trying different

00:26:38.440 --> 00:26:43.150
things. And that whole process
of, of test time scaling,

00:26:44.040 --> 00:26:47.900
Inference, is really about
thinking. And it's about

00:26:47.940 --> 00:26:51.769
reasoning, it's about planning, it's about
search, it's about... And so how could that

00:26:51.840 --> 00:26:55.620
possibly be compute light? And
we were absolutely right about

00:26:55.640 --> 00:26:59.980
that. You know, so test time scaling
is intensely compute intensive.

00:27:01.480 --> 00:27:05.440
Then the question is, okay, now we're at inference
and we're at test time scaling, what's beyond that?

00:27:06.220 --> 00:27:11.880
Well, obviously, we have now created,
you know, one agentic person,

00:27:12.920 --> 00:27:16.829
and that one agentic person has a
large language model that we've now

00:27:16.900 --> 00:27:20.700
now, you know, developed. But
during test time, that agentic

00:27:20.760 --> 00:27:24.300
system goes off and does
research and bangs on

00:27:24.340 --> 00:27:27.840
databases, and it goes out
and, you know, uses tools,

00:27:27.900 --> 00:27:31.880
and one of the most important things it
does is spins off and spawns off a whole

00:27:31.900 --> 00:27:35.560
bunch of sub-agents. Which means
we're now creating large teams.

00:27:36.640 --> 00:27:40.300
It's so much easier to scale NVIDIA by

00:27:40.360 --> 00:27:43.980
hiring more employees than
it is to scale myself.

00:27:44.160 --> 00:27:47.640
And so the next scaling law is the
agentic scaling law. It's kind of

00:27:47.700 --> 00:27:51.020
like multiplying AI.

00:27:51.720 --> 00:27:55.340
Multiplying AI, we could spin off agents
as fast as you want to spin off agents.

00:27:55.980 --> 00:27:59.840
And so, you know, I... You
know, I have four scaling laws.

00:27:59.880 --> 00:28:03.840
And as we use the agentic
systems, they're gonna create a

00:28:03.880 --> 00:28:07.500
lot more data, they're gonna create a lot
of experiences. Some of it we're gonna say,

00:28:07.780 --> 00:28:11.940
"Wow, this is really good.
We ought to memorize this."

00:28:12.180 --> 00:28:14.500
That data set then comes all
the way back to pre-training.

00:28:15.340 --> 00:28:19.120
We memorize and generalize it. We
then refine it and fine-tune it

00:28:20.380 --> 00:28:24.260
back into post-training. Then
we enhance it even more with

00:28:24.320 --> 00:28:27.860
test time, you know, and the
agents, agentic systems,

00:28:28.280 --> 00:28:31.960
you know, put it out to the
industry. And so this loop, this

00:28:32.020 --> 00:28:36.340
cycle, is gonna go on and on and on.
It kinda comes down to basically

00:28:37.740 --> 00:28:41.320
intelligence is gonna scale by
one thing, and that's compute.

00:28:41.880 --> 00:28:45.580
- But there's a tricky thing there that you
have to anticipate and predict, which

00:28:45.680 --> 00:28:49.580
is some of these components, it requires

00:28:49.780 --> 00:28:53.740
different kind of hardware to
really do it optimally. So you have

00:28:53.760 --> 00:28:57.850
to anticipate where the AI innovation's
going to lead. For example, a mixture of-

00:28:57.930 --> 00:28:58.080
- Perfect

00:28:58.090 --> 00:28:59.030
- ... experts with sparsity.

00:28:59.540 --> 00:28:59.940
- Perfect.

00:29:00.280 --> 00:29:04.160
- With hardware, you can't just
pivot on a week's notice. You

00:29:04.179 --> 00:29:06.430
have to anticipate what that's
going to look like. It has some-

00:29:06.430 --> 00:29:06.550
- So good

00:29:07.160 --> 00:29:09.360
- ... that's so scary and
difficult to do, right?

00:29:09.600 --> 00:29:14.980
- For example, These AI model architectures
are being invented about once every six

00:29:15.020 --> 00:29:22.040
months. Right? And system architectures
and hardware architectures

00:29:23.120 --> 00:29:24.900
kind of every three years.

00:29:26.160 --> 00:29:29.800
And so you need to anticipate
what likely is going to happen,

00:29:30.580 --> 00:29:31.980
you know, two, three years from now.

00:29:33.160 --> 00:29:37.070
And there's a couple ways that you could do that. First of
all, we could do research internally ourselves, and that's one

00:29:37.160 --> 00:29:39.910
of the reasons why we have basic
research, we have applied research.

00:29:40.120 --> 00:29:44.040
We create our own models.
And so we have hands-on life

00:29:44.060 --> 00:29:47.420
experience right here. This is part of
the co-design that I'm talking about.

00:29:48.200 --> 00:29:51.880
We're also the only AI company in the world that
works with literally every AI company in the world.

00:29:51.920 --> 00:29:55.780
And so to the extent that we
can, we try to get a sense

00:29:55.840 --> 00:29:59.020
of what are the challenges
that people are experiencing.

00:29:59.040 --> 00:30:02.280
- So you're listening to the whispers
across the industry, the AI labs.

00:30:02.620 --> 00:30:06.350
- That's right. You got to listen and
learn from everybody. And have a...

00:30:06.380 --> 00:30:10.160
And then the last part is to
have an architecture that's

00:30:10.180 --> 00:30:14.000
flexible, that can adapt and move
with the wind. And one of the

00:30:14.040 --> 00:30:17.780
benefits of, of CUDA is that
it's, you know, on the one hand,

00:30:18.760 --> 00:30:22.340
an incredible accelerator. On the
other hand, it's really flexible.

00:30:22.980 --> 00:30:25.640
And so that balance,
incredible balance between

00:30:26.360 --> 00:30:30.360
specialization, otherwise we
can't accelerate the CPU,

00:30:31.360 --> 00:30:35.190
versus generalization, so that we
can adapt with changing algorithms,

00:30:35.500 --> 00:30:39.340
that's really, really important.
That's the reason why CUDA has

00:30:39.380 --> 00:30:43.060
been so resilient on the
one hand, and yet we

00:30:43.100 --> 00:30:47.060
continue to enhance it. We're
at CUDA 13.2, and so we're

00:30:47.200 --> 00:30:51.000
evolving the architecture
so fast that we can stay

00:30:51.060 --> 00:30:54.980
with, you know, with
the modern algorithms.

00:30:55.620 --> 00:30:59.124
For example... When mixtures
of experts came out,

00:30:59.784 --> 00:31:03.183
That's the reason why we had
NVLink 72 instead of NVLink eight.

00:31:04.084 --> 00:31:07.864
We could now take an entire four
trillion, 10 trillion parameter model

00:31:08.264 --> 00:31:12.704
and put it in one computing domain
as if it's running on one GPU.

00:31:13.564 --> 00:31:19.464
Um, people probably didn't
notice, I said it, but

00:31:19.644 --> 00:31:21.604
if you look at the architecture of

00:31:22.464 --> 00:31:26.324
the Grace Blackwell racks,
it was completely focused on

00:31:26.624 --> 00:31:29.274
doing one thing, processing the LLM.

00:31:30.624 --> 00:31:34.224
All of a sudden, one year later,
you're looking at a Vera Rubin rack.

00:31:34.944 --> 00:31:40.284
It has storage accelerators. It has
this incredible new CPU called Vera.

00:31:41.184 --> 00:31:45.024
It has Vera Rubin and NVLink 72 to run the

00:31:45.164 --> 00:31:48.824
