00:56:11.628 --> 00:56:15.478
- Is there parallels in the NVIDIA Extreme
Systems co-design approach that you

00:56:15.608 --> 00:56:18.028
see in the way Elon approaches
systems engineering?

00:56:18.808 --> 00:56:22.468
- Well, first of all, co-design is an
ultimate systems engineering problem.

00:56:22.548 --> 00:56:26.478
And so we approach, we approach the work
that we do from that first, from that

00:56:26.568 --> 00:56:33.878
The other thing that we do and this
is, this is a philosophy, a thought,

00:56:35.188 --> 00:56:38.468
a state of mind, I guess, a method,

00:56:39.108 --> 00:56:42.958
That I started 30 years
ago, and it's called the

00:56:43.048 --> 00:56:46.928
speed of light. The speed of light is not just
about the speed. The speed of light is, is

00:56:46.988 --> 00:56:50.948
my shorthand for what's what's the

00:56:51.048 --> 00:56:54.908
limit of what physics can do.
And so every single, everything,

00:56:55.088 --> 00:56:58.708
everything that we do is compared against
the speed of light. Memory speed,

00:56:59.268 --> 00:57:06.048
Math speed, power, cost, time,
effort, number of people,

00:57:06.868 --> 00:57:12.078
manufacturing cycle time. And when you
think about latency versus throughput,

00:57:12.928 --> 00:57:16.828
When you think about cost
versus throughput, cost

00:57:16.868 --> 00:57:23.228
versus capacity, all of these things,
You test against the speed of light to

00:57:23.288 --> 00:57:30.328
achieve all of these different constraints
separately. And then when you consider it

00:57:30.398 --> 00:57:33.968
together, you know you have
to make compromises because a

00:57:34.008 --> 00:57:37.758
system that achieves extremely low
latency versus a cheap, a system that

00:57:37.768 --> 00:57:41.408
achieves very high throughput are
architected fundamentally differently.

00:57:42.028 --> 00:57:45.848
But you want to know what's the
speed of light of a system that

00:57:45.928 --> 00:57:49.888
achieves high throughput, what's
the speed of light of a system that

00:57:50.008 --> 00:57:51.408
achieves low latency?

00:57:52.248 --> 00:57:56.188
And then when you think about the total
system, you can make trade-offs. And so

00:57:56.448 --> 00:58:00.148
I force everybody to think about what's
the, what the first- the first principles,

00:58:00.348 --> 00:58:05.688
the limits- ... the physical limits,
For everything before we, you know,

00:58:06.548 --> 00:58:10.268
before we do anything.
And we test everything

00:58:10.328 --> 00:58:12.888
against that. And so that's
a good frame of mind.

00:58:13.728 --> 00:58:19.448
I don't love the other methods,
which is continuous improvement.

00:58:19.728 --> 00:58:21.888
The problem with continuous
improvement, it...

00:58:23.168 --> 00:58:27.068
First of all, you should engineer something
from first principles at the speed,

00:58:27.188 --> 00:58:31.118
you know, with speed of light thinking.
Limit it only by physical limits,

00:58:32.088 --> 00:58:39.448
and physics limits. And after that, of
course you would improve it over time. Um,

00:58:40.608 --> 00:58:44.508
but I don't like going into a problem and
somebody says, "Hey, you know, it takes 74 days

00:58:44.548 --> 00:58:49.148
to do this today-" "... Right now.
And we can do it for you in 72 days."

00:58:50.008 --> 00:58:51.957
You know, I'd rather strip
it all back to zero-

00:58:52.548 --> 00:58:55.368
... and say, "First of all, explain
to me why 74 days in the first place.

00:58:56.468 --> 00:59:00.428
And let's note, let's think about
what's possible today. And if I were

00:59:00.468 --> 00:59:04.178
to build it completely from scratch,
you know, how long would it take?"

00:59:04.608 --> 00:59:08.568
Oftentimes, you'd be surprised.
It might come to six days.

00:59:08.628 --> 00:59:12.388
Now, the rest of the six
days, the 74, could be

00:59:12.468 --> 00:59:15.968
very well-reasoned and
compromises, and, you know, cost

00:59:16.008 --> 00:59:19.968
reductions, and all kinds of different
things. But at least you know what they are.

00:59:20.848 --> 00:59:22.948
And then now that you know
that six days is possible,

00:59:24.528 --> 00:59:29.648
then the conversation from 74 to six,
surprisingly much more effective.

