the United States in so many

01:36:27.324 --> 01:36:31.284
different plants, chips,
computers, and of course, these AI

01:36:31.304 --> 01:36:33.724
factories. I'm completely aware

01:36:34.564 --> 01:36:39.504
that, that... And I have the
benefit, and this is a real

01:36:40.364 --> 01:36:44.744
a real gift with mainstream investors,

01:36:45.624 --> 01:36:50.224
teachers, policemen who have
somehow, for whatever reason,

01:36:51.064 --> 01:36:54.984
invested in NVIDIA or because
they watched Jim Cramer bought

01:36:55.024 --> 01:37:01.954
some stock and now are millionaires.
And I am completely aware of

01:37:02.024 --> 01:37:06.724
that circumstance. I'm aware of
the circumstance that NVIDIA,

01:37:07.804 --> 01:37:13.164
is central to a very large network of

01:37:13.224 --> 01:37:15.714
ecosystem partners behind
us and downstream from us.

01:37:16.784 --> 01:37:21.814
And so the way I deal with that is
exactly what I just did. I reason about

01:37:23.344 --> 01:37:24.864
what is... what is it that we're doing?

01:37:26.044 --> 01:37:29.684
What is it causing? What's the
impact that has on other people

01:37:29.744 --> 01:37:32.564
benefit, you know, positively or even,

01:37:33.784 --> 01:37:36.944
even through great burden,
for example, to supply chain?

01:37:38.684 --> 01:37:43.324
And the question is, therefore,
what are you gonna do about it?

01:37:44.764 --> 01:37:49.764
In almost everything that I feel, I
break it down, I reason about, "Okay,

01:37:50.564 --> 01:37:53.743
"what's the circumstance? What
has changed? What's hard?

01:37:54.644 --> 01:37:59.104
And what am I gonna do about it?" And I
break it down, decompose the problem,

01:38:00.284 --> 01:38:06.184
and the decomposition
of these circumstances

01:38:07.484 --> 01:38:11.384
turns it into manageable things that I
can do. And the only thing after that

01:38:11.664 --> 01:38:15.494
I could do is, "Did you do it?
Did you either do it or did you

01:38:15.524 --> 01:38:18.154
get somebody else to do it?
And if you didn't do it,

01:38:18.964 --> 01:38:22.714
you reasoned that you need to do it, and you didn't
do it, and you didn't get anybody else to do it,

01:38:23.304 --> 01:38:30.328
then stop crying about it." You
know? And so- ... so I'm fairly

01:38:31.198 --> 01:38:35.128
Tough on myself. And, but I
also break things down so that,

01:38:35.448 --> 01:38:39.328
so that I don't panic. I can go

01:38:39.348 --> 01:38:43.338
to sleep because I've made the list
of things that needed to be done, and

01:38:43.408 --> 01:38:47.208
I've made sure that everything that
could put our company in harm's way,

01:38:47.708 --> 01:38:51.648
could put my partners in harm's way, put
our industry in harm's way, I've told

01:38:51.768 --> 01:38:55.928
somebody. Everything that I feel

01:38:57.008 --> 01:39:00.928
could put anybody in harm's way,
I've told someone. And I've told

01:39:00.968 --> 01:39:04.948
that someone who could do something about
it. And so I've gotten it off my chest

01:39:05.528 --> 01:39:10.568
or I'm doing something about it. And so
after that, Lex, what else can you do?

01:39:10.608 --> 01:39:14.528
- So given all the insane,
intense amount of suffering

01:39:15.148 --> 01:39:22.228
on the journey of building up NVIDIA,
have you hit low points psychologically?

01:39:22.328 --> 01:39:27.208
- Oh, yeah. Oh, yeah. Sure.
All the time. All the time.

01:39:27.248 --> 01:39:27.688
- And there—

01:39:27.718 --> 01:39:27.948
- All the time.

01:39:27.968 --> 01:39:31.188
- ... you just break down
the problem into pieces?

01:39:31.468 --> 01:39:31.878
- Yeah. Yeah.

01:39:31.928 --> 01:39:33.168
- See what you could do about it?

01:39:33.808 --> 01:39:38.228
- And, and part of, and, you know, Lex,
part of it, part of it is forgetting.

01:39:39.068 --> 01:39:42.828
One of the most important attributes
of AI learning, as you know, is,

01:39:43.068 --> 01:39:46.408
right? Systematic forgetting. You,
you need to know when to forget

01:39:47.028 --> 01:39:50.548
some things. You can't memorize everything.
You can't keep everything and, and,

01:39:51.168 --> 01:39:54.668
you know, you, you want to— you don't want to
carry everything. One of the things that I do very

01:39:54.708 --> 01:39:58.488
quickly is decompose the problem,
I reason about the problem, and I

01:39:58.728 --> 01:40:00.918
share the load with it. When
I say I tell everybody,

01:40:01.768 --> 01:40:05.248
I'm essentially sharing that
burden. As quickly as possible.

01:40:06.548 --> 01:40:10.348
Whatever worries me, tell somebody
else. Don't just keep it. You know,

01:40:10.388 --> 01:40:16.828
don't freak them out. Decompose the
problem into smaller parts and get

01:40:16.928 --> 01:40:20.308
people to, so, and, and inspire them to
be able to go do something about it.

01:40:20.948 --> 01:40:23.698
But part of it is just, just
forgetting. You know, like,

01:40:24.548 --> 01:40:28.368
a lot of it is you gotta be tough on
yourself. You know, just come on, stop

01:40:28.428 --> 01:40:32.408
crying about it. Let's get going. You know?
And, and then you get out of bed. And then

01:40:32.468 --> 01:40:36.268
the other part is, is you,
you're attracted to the

01:40:36.338 --> 01:40:39.908
next shiny light, the next future,
you know, the next opportunity, the

01:40:40.008 --> 01:40:42.378
next, "Okay, that's behind
us. Let— what's next?"

01:40:43.268 --> 01:40:46.688
It's a lot, I think, you know, you
watch this with great athletes. They,

01:40:47.388 --> 01:40:49.708
they just worry about the next point.

01:40:50.228 --> 01:40:56.548
The last point is behind them. The
embarrassment, the, you know— the setback.

01:40:56.708 --> 01:41:00.428
You know, and, and then, and because
I do so much of my job publicly,

01:41:01.628 --> 01:41:05.528
you know? Lex, you do a fair amount of your
job publicly too. And so, so I do a lot of my

01:41:05.588 --> 01:41:09.498
job publicly. And so you
know, I say a lot of

01:41:09.528 --> 01:41:13.438
things that, that seem sensible
at the time or funny at the time,

01:41:13.448 --> 01:41:16.868
mostly it's just because it's funny to
me at the time. And then, you know, you

01:41:17.168 --> 01:41:19.088
reflect on it, it's
less funny, but, but...

01:41:20.008 --> 01:41:23.948
- Yeah. No, trust me, I know. But
you basically allow yourself to

01:41:23.988 --> 01:41:27.908
be pulled by the light of the future.
Forget the past and just keep-

01:41:27.968 --> 01:41:28.308
- That's right.

01:41:28.568 --> 01:41:32.068
- ... keep working towards that. I mean,
you did say, there's this kind of

01:41:32.868 --> 01:41:37.088
famous thing you said that if
you knew how hard it would be

01:41:38.048 --> 01:41:41.948
to build NVIDIA it turned
out to be, what is it? A

01:41:42.008 --> 01:41:46.388
million times more hard than you
anticipated that you wouldn't do it.

01:41:46.988 --> 01:41:47.448
- Yeah, right.

01:41:47.458 --> 01:41:50.298
- Um, but isn't... You
know, when I hear that,

01:41:51.328 --> 01:41:53.508
that's probably true about
everything worth doing, right?

01:41:53.748 --> 01:41:58.228
- Exactly. That is, by the way, what I
was trying to explain, is that there's

01:41:59.068 --> 01:42:07.448
a, there's a incredible superpower of
being, being have a, the mind of a child.

01:42:07.968 --> 01:42:10.697
You know? And I say to myself
oftentimes when I look at something,

01:42:11.628 --> 01:42:19.008
and almost, almost everything, My first
thought is, "How hard can it be?"

01:42:19.408 --> 01:42:23.358
You know? And so you get yourself
into that mode, how hard could

01:42:23.388 --> 01:42:27.308
it be? And, and nobody's ever done it. It

01:42:27.348 --> 01:42:30.808
looks gigantic. It's gonna cost
hundreds of billions of dollars.

01:42:31.268 --> 01:42:34.888
It's gonna take, you know, all this... And you
just go, "Yeah, but how hard could it be?"

01:42:35.328 --> 01:42:37.068
You know? How hard could it be?

01:42:37.108 --> 01:42:41.098
And so you gotta get yourself into
that state of mind. You don't

01:42:41.128 --> 01:42:45.107
wanna, you don't wanna
actually over simulate

01:42:45.167 --> 01:42:48.818
everything and all the setbacks and all
the trials and tribulations and all

01:42:48.848 --> 01:42:52.368
the disappointments. You don't wanna simulate
all that in advance. You don't wanna know that.

01:42:53.008 --> 01:42:56.328
You don't, you wanna go into a new
experience thinking it's gonna be perfect,

01:42:56.928 --> 01:43:00.788
it's gonna be great, it's gonna be
incredibly fun. And then while you're there,

01:43:01.588 --> 01:43:02.528
you know, you need to have,

01:43:03.528 --> 01:43:07.088
you need to have endurance, you need to
have grit, so that when the setbacks

01:43:07.108 --> 01:43:10.728
actually happened, and those
setbacks are gonna surprise you, the

01:43:10.768 --> 01:43:14.668
disappointments are gonna surprise
you, you know, the embarrassments are

01:43:14.708 --> 01:43:17.048
gonna surprise you, the humiliations
are gonna surprise you.

01:43:17.988 --> 01:43:21.908
You just can't let... Now you just gotta
turn on the other bit, which is just forget

01:43:21.948 --> 01:43:25.768
about it. Move on, keep moving.
And, and to the extent that,

01:43:27.468 --> 01:43:30.348
to the extent that my assumptions

01:43:31.188 --> 01:43:34.628
about the future and why the
future is gonna manifest,

01:43:36.168 --> 01:43:38.548
so long as those
assumptions and that input

01:43:40.068 --> 01:43:43.748
doesn't change or didn't change
materially, then I should

01:43:43.768 --> 01:43:48.808
expect that the output won't change. And
so my simulated output of the future

01:43:49.608 --> 01:43:52.188
is still gonna happen. And
if it's still gonna happen,

01:43:53.328 --> 01:43:57.208
I'm still gonna go after it. I believe it's
gonna, you know, and so there's a combination

01:43:57.248 --> 01:44:00.128
of two or three human characteristics,

01:44:01.728 --> 01:44:04.588
the ability to go into a, into
an experience fresh-minded,

01:44:05.528 --> 01:44:10.348
the ability to forget the setbacks,
the ability to believe in yourself,

01:44:11.768 --> 01:44:15.448
you know, to believe what you believe
and stay, stay true to that belief.

01:44:16.588 --> 01:44:23.108
But you're constantly reevaluating. This
combination of three, four, five things

01:44:23.968 --> 01:44:27.828
I think is, is really
important for resilience. And,

01:44:27.908 --> 01:44:31.905
and... and, you know, I'm fortunate that,

01:44:32.176 --> 01:44:36.096
that whatever life experiences led
to this, I've got kind of those

01:44:36.136 --> 01:44:39.776
four, five things. You know, I'm
always curious, always learning.

01:44:40.516 --> 01:44:44.316
I'm always learning from everybody,
you know? I'm always asking my...

01:44:44.416 --> 01:44:48.196
And because I'm humble about
everything, I'm always thinking,

01:44:48.686 --> 01:44:52.496
"Gosh, they did that so nicely. They
did that so wonderfully." You know,

01:44:53.076 --> 01:44:56.756
I wonder what they're thinking through.
How do they... You know, so I'm

01:44:56.856 --> 01:45:00.796
simulating everybody. In a lot of ways,
you know, I'm emulating almost everybody

01:45:00.896 --> 01:45:04.756
I watch, right? You're empathetic
towards everything that they

01:45:04.796 --> 01:45:08.485
do that you're observing and
respect. And, and so you're

01:45:08.485 --> 01:45:10.336
constantly learning and, you know.

01:45:10.976 --> 01:45:14.956
- You're now one of the wealthiest
people on Earth. One of the

01:45:14.976 --> 01:45:17.396
most successful humans on Earth.

01:45:18.236 --> 01:45:21.936
Is it harder to be humble and to
be able to... Do you feel the

01:45:21.976 --> 01:45:27.296
effect of money and power and fame
in making it harder for you to

01:45:28.836 --> 01:45:32.396
sort of be wrong in your own head? Enough

01:45:32.476 --> 01:45:36.086
to hear out an opinion of
somebody else when they

01:45:36.116 --> 01:45:38.806
disagree with you and learn from
them? Those kinds of things.

01:45:41.756 --> 01:45:45.916
- Um, surprisingly, no. And I would,
I would actually go the other way.

01:45:46.596 --> 01:45:50.956
Because I do so much of my
work publicly, when I'm wrong,

01:45:51.796 --> 01:45:52.876
pretty much everybody sees it.

01:45:53.756 --> 01:45:55.556
- You get humbled. Fair enough.

01:45:55.636 --> 01:45:59.276
- And when I'm wrong, when I'm
wrong or it didn't turn out that

01:45:59.316 --> 01:46:07.176
way or you know, I mean, most of the
things that, that I say outside I'm fairly

01:46:07.216 --> 01:46:10.676
certain about. And the reason for
that is because, because it's gonna

01:46:10.996 --> 01:46:14.566
impact somebody else and I want to be
quite concerned about that and quite,

01:46:14.576 --> 01:46:19.286
circumspect about that. For stuff that,
that I'm reasoning about inside a meeting,

01:46:20.096 --> 01:46:23.696
you know a lot of things could
turn out differently. And

01:46:23.756 --> 01:46:27.656
so, but it doesn't ever stop me from
reasoning. The way that the way that I

01:46:27.716 --> 01:46:29.176
manage and lead, I,

01:46:30.016 --> 01:46:33.916
you know, I'm constantly reasoning in front of
people. And even when I'm talking to you, you can

01:46:33.956 --> 01:46:35.446
kind of see me kind of
reasoning through things.

01:46:35.956 --> 01:46:39.636
And I want to make sure that you understand
what I'm saying not because I told you-

01:46:40.416 --> 01:46:42.665
... because I'm so humble about
what I'm about to tell you.

01:46:43.476 --> 01:46:45.686
I kind of show you the
steps that I got there.

01:46:46.236 --> 01:46:50.176
And then you can decide whether you believe
what I said in the end. And so I'm doing that

01:46:50.276 --> 01:46:51.286
all day long in meetings.

01:46:52.276 --> 01:46:56.196
With all of my employees, I'm constantly
reasoning through, "Let me tell you what, how I

01:46:56.256 --> 01:46:59.776
see it." And then I reason through
it. It gives everybody the

01:46:59.836 --> 01:47:03.706
opportunity to intercept and say,
"I disagree with that part."

01:47:04.376 --> 01:47:08.316
The nice thing about reasoning through
things and letting people interact with

01:47:08.356 --> 01:47:10.916
it is that they don't have to
disagree with your outcome.

01:47:12.316 --> 01:47:14.276
They can disagree with
your reasoning steps.

01:47:15.196 --> 01:47:18.656
And they could pull me in different
directions, and then we can reason forward.

01:47:19.736 --> 01:47:24.036
And so we're kind of, you know, collective

01:47:25.016 --> 01:47:28.536
path searching method. And
it's really fantastic.

01:47:29.176 --> 01:47:30.046
- Yeah, you have this

01:47:30.916 --> 01:47:34.476
way about you of ... When you're
explaining stuff, I can feel you

01:47:34.576 --> 01:47:38.396
actually reasoning on
the spot about it with a

01:47:38.456 --> 01:47:42.376
constant open-mindedness where you
could ... I could feel like I could

01:47:42.456 --> 01:47:44.016
steer your thinking.

01:47:44.236 --> 01:47:48.216
And that's a, that's really beautiful that
you've been able to maintain that after so many

01:47:48.276 --> 01:47:49.915
years of success, and pain.

01:47:50.616 --> 01:47:54.756
I think sometimes pain makes you
close, closes you down a bit.

01:47:55.426 --> 01:47:55.676
- Mm-hmm. Yeah.

01:47:56.096 --> 01:47:57.505
- And I think to maintain-

01:47:57.526 --> 01:47:59.396
- Yeah. Tolerance for
embarrassment, I think is...

01:47:59.936 --> 01:48:03.255
- Yes, that's ... The tolerance
... I mean, that's a real thing.

01:48:03.536 --> 01:48:07.216
Is many years of embarrassing
yourself. Even those meetings

01:48:07.396 --> 01:48:11.256
knowing that there's people around
you where you declared one idea and

01:48:11.596 --> 01:48:13.346
it was shown that that idea was wrong-

01:48:13.346 --> 01:48:17.316
... and be able to admit that and to grow from
that. That's not, that's very difficult on a human

01:48:17.376 --> 01:48:17.636
level.

01:48:17.896 --> 01:48:21.836
- Yeah. Well, you know. They
knew that recently my first

01:48:21.916 --> 01:48:24.676
job was, you know, cleaning toilets, so.

01:48:25.376 --> 01:48:28.796
- I'm glad you maintained
that same spirit of Denny's

01:48:29.636 --> 01:48:33.576
the, the work. I mean, that, that was beautiful.
Your whole journey from, starting from Denny's is a

01:48:33.636 --> 01:48:40.756
beautiful one. Let me ask you about
video games. So I'm a big gaming fan.

01:48:41.536 --> 01:48:47.436
So I have to say thank you to NVIDIA
for many years of incredible graphics.

01:48:47.496 --> 01:48:51.156
- By the way, GeForce is
our still, to this day-

01:48:51.536 --> 01:48:54.416
... our number one marketing strategy.

01:48:55.556 --> 01:48:59.616
Right. People learn about NVIDIA
while they're in their teenage years.

01:49:00.036 --> 01:49:03.956
And then they go to college and they
know who NVIDIA is and then in beginning

01:49:03.996 --> 01:49:07.736
is just, you know, playing Call of Duty, you
know? You know, Fortnite. And then later

01:49:08.056 --> 01:49:13.176
they're using CUDA, and then later they're
using NVIDIA and, you know, Blender and

01:49:14.256 --> 01:49:16.276
Dassault and Autodesk.

01:49:16.306 --> 01:49:19.976
- Yeah. I mean, I should say I
mentioned to a friend that I'm

01:49:20.136 --> 01:49:25.196
talking with you. He said, "Oh,
they make great gaming GPUs."

01:49:25.316 --> 01:49:26.176
- Yeah, exactly.

01:49:26.496 --> 01:49:26.726
- It's like-

01:49:26.736 --> 01:49:27.076
- Exactly.

01:49:27.096 --> 01:49:30.896
- You know, there's more
to it, but, yeah, yeah,

01:49:31.036 --> 01:49:34.876
people really love the ... It really brought
a lot of joy to a lot of people. The,

01:49:35.516 --> 01:49:38.036
the, the hardware really
brings these worlds to life.

01:49:38.836 --> 01:49:43.976
There was some controversy
around this with DLSS 5.

01:49:44.156 --> 01:49:47.636
Can you explain to me the
drama around this? Uh, I guess

01:49:48.456 --> 01:49:54.356
people, the gamers online were concerned
that it makes games look like AI slop.

01:49:54.496 --> 01:49:56.315
Uh, what do you think of this drama?

01:49:56.356 --> 01:50:00.396
- Yeah. Uh, I think their
perspective makes sense

01:50:01.316 --> 01:50:05.036
and I could see where they're coming from,
because I don't love AI slop myself.

01:50:05.776 --> 01:50:09.916
You know, all of the AI
generated content increasingly,

01:50:10.796 --> 01:50:13.636
um, looks similar and
they're all beautiful,

01:50:14.576 --> 01:50:18.096
and I can... So I can... I'm empathetic
towards what they're thinking.

01:50:18.836 --> 01:50:23.516
That's just not what DLSS 5 is trying
to do. I showed several examples of it.

01:50:24.336 --> 01:50:26.436
But DLSS 5 is

01:50:27.336 --> 01:50:34.236
3D conditioned, 3D guided. It's ground
truth structure data guided. And so the

01:50:34.316 --> 01:50:39.528
artist determined the geometry.
We are completely truthful.... to

01:50:40.528 --> 01:50:42.948
the geometry maintains
in every single frame.

01:50:43.768 --> 01:50:50.518
It's conditioned by the textures, the
artistry of the artist. And so every single

01:50:50.568 --> 01:50:54.308
frame, it enhances but it doesn't change

01:50:54.368 --> 01:50:57.698
anything. Now, the question is,
the question about enhancing,

01:50:59.148 --> 01:51:01.318
DLSS 5 also lets, because it's,

01:51:02.148 --> 01:51:06.088
the system is open, you could train
your own models to determine,

01:51:06.728 --> 01:51:10.428
and you could even in the future prompt
it. You know, I want it to be a toon

01:51:10.488 --> 01:51:14.348
shader. I want it to look like this
kinda, you know, so you can give it even

01:51:14.388 --> 01:51:18.157
an example. And it would
generate in the style of that,

01:51:19.108 --> 01:51:22.808
all consistent with the
artistry, you know, the

01:51:22.948 --> 01:51:28.148
style, the intent of the artist.
And so all of that is done

01:51:29.368 --> 01:51:33.408
for the artist, so that they can create
something that is more beautiful,

01:51:34.288 --> 01:51:38.088
But still in the style that
they want. I think that

01:51:38.888 --> 01:51:42.808
they got the impression
that the games are gonna

01:51:42.868 --> 01:51:46.818
come out the way the games are
shipped the way they do, and then

01:51:46.848 --> 01:51:50.648
we're gonna post-process it. That's
not what DLSS is intended to do.

01:51:50.748 --> 01:51:54.628
DLSS is integrated with
the artist, and so it's,

01:51:54.908 --> 01:51:58.748
it's about giving the artist
the tool of AI, the tool of

01:51:58.808 --> 01:52:00.968
generative AI. They could
decide not to use it, you know?

01:52:01.448 --> 01:52:03.848
